### Description

Currently, `provideSignalFormsConfig()` allows us to define CSS classes that will be applied to form fields based on predicate functions, like this:

```ts
// ...
import { provideSignalFormsConfig } from '@angular/forms/signals';

export const appConfig: ApplicationConfig = {
  providers: [
    // ...
    provideSignalFormsConfig({
      classes: {
        valid: (state) => state.valid(),
        error: (state) => state.touched() && state.errors().length > 0,
        pending: (state) => state.pending(),
      },
    }),
  ],
};
```

This is great for adding CSS styles based on a field’s state.

However, in some cases I also want to set specific HTML attributes based on a field’s state. Such attributes could be ARIA attributes or something like a `data-*` attribute. It would be helpful if we could also dynamically set these attributes via a global configuration using predicate functions for the field state.

### Proposed solution

My proposed solution is similar to the once which currently exists for the CSS classes but it should apply the attributes and the return type of the predicate function is the value assigned to the attribute.

```ts
// ...
import { provideSignalFormsConfig } from '@angular/forms/signals';

export const appConfig: ApplicationConfig = {
  providers: [
    // ...
    provideSignalFormsConfig({
      attributes: {
        'aria-invalid': (state) => state().touched() && !state().pending() ? state().errors().length > 0 : undefined,
        'aria-busy': (state) => state.pending() || undefined,
        'data-icon-ok': (state) => state.valid() || undefined,
      },
    }),
  ],
};
```

### Alternatives considered

My proposed solution is similar to the one that currently exists for CSS classes, but it should apply attributes instead. The return value of the predicate function would be the value assigned to the attribute.

